{
  "text": "where r is the distance between the point (x,y,z) and the origin of the coordinate system, and G is the gravitational constant. In order to evaluate Eq. (5), the variables (x,y,z) are substituted by the limits 1 1 1 2 2 2 ( , , , , , ) x y z x y z , giving a total of 48 terms per prism [CITATION_1] . The standard topographic mass-density 0 \u03c1 of 2670 kg m -3 was used. We use 1 z = 0 and 2 z = RTM z , so that the prism heights 2 1 z z \u2212 represent the residual elevations. Equation (5) is based on a planar approximation [CITATION_2] , however, the effect of Earth curvature is taken into account here by a vertical shift of the prism as a function of the distance between each prism and the RTM computation point (cf. Forsberg 1984, p. 111) .",
